      "snippet": "Address not found Your message wasn&#39;t delivered to mark@trustwellbank.com because the address couldn&#39;t be found, or is unable to receive mail. The response from the remote server was: 550 No",
      "body": "Hi Mark,\r\n\r\nBelow is a concise overview of the standard procedures we follow when\r\nassisting customers and reporting issues. I’ve also included a couple\r\nof internal resources that should be useful.\r\n\r\nHandling customer inquiries\r\n1. Verify the customer’s identity (photo ID + account verification questions).\r\n2. Listen to and clarify the request, taking notes in the CRM.\r\n3. If the request is routine (balance inquiry, statement print-out,\r\netc.), process it immediately and confirm completion with the\r\ncustomer.\r\n4. For requests involving transactions, follow the step-by-step\r\nworkflow in the Teller Operations Guide (see link below) and obtain\r\nthe required approvals for amounts above the daily threshold.\r\n5. Document the interaction in the CRM before closing the session.\r\n\r\nIssue-reporting protocol\r\n1. Determine whether the issue is routine (e.g., minor system glitch)\r\nor critical (e.g., suspected fraud).\r\n2. Routine issues: open a ticket in the Service Desk portal and attach\r\nany screenshots or error codes.\r\n3. Critical issues: call the Help Desk, then email the ticket number\r\nand a brief description so they can fast-track it.\r\n4. Escalate anything that affects branch operations or customer\r\nsecurity to your branch manager, who will coordinate further steps.\r\n\r\nKey resources\r\n• Teller Operations Guide – Section 2 covers everyday transactions;\r\nSection 4 details approval levels.\r\n• Service Desk Portal – use the “Banking Systems” queue for technical\r\nproblems and the “Risk/Fraud” queue for security concerns.\r\n• Help Desk email: internal-help@trustwellbank.com (monitored 7 AM–7 PM).\r\n• Regional Managers Contact List – available in the intranet directory\r\nif you need branch-level escalation.\r\n\r\nLet me know if you’d like to walk through any scenario in more detail,\r\nand I’ll be happy to set up a quick call.\r\n\r\nBest,\r\nJane\r\n"
    },
    {
      "id": "196d1380297dcb03",
      "subject": "Credit Building Strategies for New Immigrants",
      "from": "kate@gmail.com",
      "date": "Mon, 21 Feb 2022 10:15:00 +0000",
      "snippet": "Hi John, I hope this message finds you well. I&#39;m reaching out to share some insights on how we can assist the new members of our immigrant community in building their credit history in the United",
      "body": "Hi John,\n\nI hope this message finds you well. I'm reaching out to share some insights on how we can assist the new members of our immigrant community in building their credit history in the United States. As you know, establishing a good credit score is crucial for them to navigate financial matters here. Any advice or resources you could share would be greatly appreciated.\n\nIn particular, we took on the case of Osman, who had recently moved to the U.S. with dreams of building a new life. Initially facing the challenge of a nonexistent credit history and starting with a score of 300, our goal was ambitious but clear: to help him reach a fair credit score of at least 670 within a year. Through a tailored strategy that included securing a credit card designed for newcomers, obtaining a credit-builder loan, and ensuring his rent and utility payments were reported to the credit bureaus, Osman's financial profile began to transform. Remarkably, not only did Osman reach our target; he surpassed it, achieving a credit score of 690 within the year. This success opened new doors for him, including eligibility for competitive loan rates and the possibility of homeownership, marking a significant milestone in his journey towards financial stability and independence.\n\nBest regards,\nKate\n"
    }
